Introduction to Computer Vision: Plant Seedlings Classification¶

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

In recent times, the field of agriculture has been in urgent need of modernizing, since the amount of manual work people need to put in to check if plants are growing correctly is still highly extensive. Despite several advances in agricultural technology, people working in the agricultural industry still need to have the ability to sort and recognize different plants and weeds, which takes a lot of time and effort in the long term. The potential is ripe for this trillion-dollar industry to be greatly impacted by technological innovations that cut down on the requirement for manual labor, and this is where Artificial Intelligence can actually benefit the workers in this field, as the time and energy required to identify plant seedlings will be greatly shortened by the use of AI and Deep Learning. The ability to do so far more efficiently and even more effectively than experienced manual labor, could lead to better crop yields, the freeing up of human inolvement for higher-order agricultural decision making, and in the long term will result in more sustainable environmental practices in agriculture as well.

Objective¶

The aim of this project is to Build a Convolutional Neural Netowrk to classify plant seedlings into their respective categories.

Data Dictionary¶

The Aarhus University Signal Processing group, in collaboration with the University of Southern Denmark, has recently released a dataset containing images of unique plants belonging to 12 different species.

  • The dataset can be download from Olympus.
  • The data file names are:
    • images.npy
    • Labels.csv

  • Due to the large volume of data, the images were converted to the images.npy file and the labels are also put into Labels.csv, so that you can work on the data/project seamlessly without having to worry about the high data volume.

  • The goal of the project is to create a classifier capable of determining a plant's species from an image.

List of Species

  • Black-grass
  • Charlock
  • Cleavers
  • Common Chickweed
  • Common Wheat
  • Fat Hen
  • Loose Silky-bent
  • Maize
  • Scentless Mayweed
  • Shepherds Purse
  • Small-flowered Cranesbill
  • Sugar beet

Data Overview¶

Understand the shape of the dataset¶

In [189]:
images.shape
Out[189]:
(4750, 128, 128, 3)

The length of the data is 4750. That's how many images we have to work with.

Each image is 128 by 128, so the 2nd and 3rd dimensions correspond to the 128x128 pixels in each image.

Each pixel has 3 numbers associated with it, representing the color values. Presumably they represent RGB numbers but it's important to confirm that.

We do have some imbalance, but it's not egregious. The ratio between the most and least common is about 3:1. This is close enough to balanced that a model that just guesses the mode is not going to be very successful, and we can use accuracy as our metric of choice.

Data Pre-Processing¶

Convert the BGR images to RGB images.¶

I first want to check that these are not already RGB. Let's look at two pixels from one image where the color is clear. I'm gonna use Image #2424 from above, where there's a nice blue rock next to the green plant.

In [192]:
#Plot half the image so I know where the x and y go.
plt.imshow(images[2424][:64])
Out[192]:
<matplotlib.image.AxesImage at 0x269b44d2e88>

The pixel at (40, 45) is mostly blue and the one at (60, 50) is mostly green. In our numpy arrays, it uses Y first and then X. Let's get the color values at those points.

In [193]:
print(f"Blue Point: {images[2424][45][40]}")
print(f"Green Point: {images[2424][50][60]}")

Blue Point: [24 54 97]
Green Point: [28 67 55]

It looks like our Blue Point has the highest value in the third column, and the Green Point's highest value is the second. That leaves the first to be Red.

The images are already in RGB, then. Wonderful.

Resize the images¶

As the size of the images is large, it may be computationally expensive to train on these larger images; therefore, it is preferable to reduce the image size from 128 to 64.

In [194]:
#We're going to reduce each dimension by a factor of 2 by cutting out half the rows and columns.

small_images = []
for image in images:
    small_image = image[::2, ::2]  #Get pixels from every other row/column
    small_images.append(small_image)

Data Preparation for Modeling¶

  • Before you proceed to build a model, you need to split the data into train, test, and validation to be able to evaluate the model that you build on the train data
  • You'll have to encode categorical features and scale the pixel values.
  • You will build a model using the train data and then check its performance

Split the dataset

In [296]:
#Zip images with labels, then shuffle
data = [
    (image, label) for image, label in zip(small_images, labels['Label'].values)
]

np.random.seed(256)
np.random.shuffle(data)

#Make splits, then separate images from labels again
cut1 = int(0.8*len(data))
cut2 = int(0.9*len(data))
training_data = data[:cut1]
validation_data = data[cut1:cut2]
testing_data = data[cut2:]

X_train, y_train = (np.array([i for i,j in training_data]), np.array([j for i,j in training_data]))
X_val, y_val = (np.array([i for i,j in validation_data]), np.array([j for i,j in validation_data]))
X_test, y_test = (np.array([i for i,j in testing_data]), np.array([j for i,j in testing_data]))

# Intializing a sequential model
model = Sequential()

# Adding first conv layer with 64 filters and kernel size 3x3 , padding 'same' provides the output size same as the input size
model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same", input_shape=(64, 64, 3)))

# Adding max pooling to reduce the size of output of first conv layer
model.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding = 'same'))

model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
model.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding = 'same'))

# flattening the output of the conv layer after max pooling to make it ready for creating dense connections
model.add(Flatten())

# Adding a fully connected dense layer with 100 neurons    
model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.3))
model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.3))

# Adding the output layer with 10 neurons and activation functions as softmax since this is a multi-class classification problem  
model.add(Dense(len(lb.classes_), activation='softmax'))

# Using SGD Optimizer
opt = SGD(learning_rate=0.01, momentum=0.9)

# Compile model
model.compile(optimizer=opt, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Generating the summary of the model
model.summary()

We can see that even our relatively simple CNN is overfitting quickly and badly. In just 7 epochs it has 60% accuracy on the training data but an abysmal rate on the validation data. Whatever it's learning from the training set is not generalizing at all.

I could spend a lot of time trying to add more layers and complexity to the model, but I worry that will only make it even more proficient at overfitting. The problem likely lies in the data, and data augmentation should help provide training data for the model that will filter out some specific but irrelevant image features it may be using.

First let's look at a confusion matrices to see if there's more insight.

In [456]:
#Make an NxN matrix
confusion_matrix = [[0 for n in range(len(lb.classes_))] for n in range(len(lb.classes_))]

#Fill in the NxN matrix with correct labels and model predictions
for i, pred in enumerate(model.predict(X_train)):
    idx_actual = list(y_train_e[i]).index(1)
    idx_pred = list(pred).index(max(pred))
    
    confusion_matrix[idx_actual][idx_pred] += 1

plt.figure(figsize=(12,10))
plt.title("Confusion Matrix on Training Set")
sns.heatmap(confusion_matrix, annot=True)
Out[456]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x269a0f20c48>

The diagonals are the correct guesses. The row is the correct label and the column is the label guessed.

Even on the training data we can see where some known weaknesses are.

  • The model is poor at detecting classes 2 and 9 at all, as the guesses for those cases are widepsread among all the others.
  • It is conflating classes 0, 4, and 6 together, guessing them all as class 6.
  • When it doesn't know, it seems to just throw up class 3 or 8 as its default prediction.

Model Performance Improvement¶

Data Augmentation¶

Remember, data augmentation should not be used in the validation/test data set.

In [446]:
#Organize training data by class
X_train_by_class = {n: [] for n in range(len(lb.classes_))}
for i, image in enumerate(X_train):
    label = list(y_train_e[i]).index(1)
    X_train_by_class[label].append(image)

#Define the image generator
datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
                             horizontal_flip = True,
                             vertical_flip = False, 
                             height_shift_range= 0.1,
                             width_shift_range=0.1, 
                             rotation_range=20, 
                             shear_range = 0.1,
                             zoom_range=0.1
                            )

#For each class, generate an equal number of augmented images from the training data
X_train_gen = []
y_train_gen = []
for label in X_train_by_class:
    y_train_by_class = [0 for n in range(len(lb.classes_))]
    y_train_by_class[label] = 1
    y_train_by_class_e = np.array([y_train_by_class for m in range(len(X_train_by_class[label]))])
    x_array = np.array(X_train_by_class[label])

    #For this class, generate 20 augmented images 20 times (400 total), shuffling each time
    for i in range(20):
        train_generator = datagen.flow(
            x_array, 
            y_train_by_class_e, 
            shuffle=True, 
            batch_size=20
        )
        
        gen_images, gen_labels = next(train_generator)
        for image in gen_images:
            X_train_gen.append(image)
        for label in gen_labels:
            y_train_gen.append(label)

        
X_train_gen = np.array(X_train_gen)
y_train_gen = np.array(y_train_gen)

This is what I don't understand. The data is balanced, and when predicting from training data its predictions are diverse. When we apply the model to the validation set, it just... breaks. It found very little opportunity to guess anything other than classes 3 and 7 whereas it was finding plenty before. Whatever features the model is picking up in the training set is just not present in the validation set -- in other words we've massively overfit in training.

It's possible that the backgrounds in these images are just too distracting. Sometimes there are rocks, sometimes there are barcode-looking borders. The plants themselves, especially the long and wispy ones, are sometimes hard to detect even for humans. Data augmentation helped a little bit by diversifying the important features and made the predictions slightly more generalizable, but they were still too subtle, it would appear.

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶

  • "Garbage in, garbage out" remains as true as it ever was. I understand that reducing the file images by 3/4ths was important for computation time, but the quality of the remaining images seemed to be really impacted and I think this was one cause for why actually capturing the images was so difficult for the models.

  • Speaking of computation, having more resources seems especially valuable. The more training you can do, the better the model can perform. With computer vision, especially, there is a lot of information coming through in these images that have nothing to do with the target -- probably 50-90% of each image was background. In order to train a model to pick up on these subtleties, you need a sufficiently complex model with a lot of high-quality data.

  • Data Augmentation is one way to make up for lack of data, but it's not always an actual improvement. It is possible to add even more junk to your training data, making it even worse.
